{"title_page": "Gurdwara Gobind Ghat", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurdwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 = \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in India\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = India\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = Guru\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = \n}}\n'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Kangan Ghat,  is situated on the bank of river [[Ganges]], about 200 yards from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]. It is the place where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold bangle, and where he blessed mental peace to Pandit Shiv Dutt, by giving him the knowledge of Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji. Guru Sahib Ji taught him what the nine gurus had preached.\n\nThe [[ghat]] is associated whith Guru Gobind Singh's childhood, as he was often found playing with his playmates on the banks of the [[Ganges]].  This [[ghat]] about one furlong from [[Takht Shri Harmandir Saheb]] and is marked by a gateway over which this [[Gurdwara]] is situated in a single room. The river has since receded away to the north.\nhttps://www.allaboutsikhs.com/gurudwaras-in-india/gurdwara-gobind-ghat-patna-bihar\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurdwara Gobind Ghat is also known as [[Gurdwara Kangan Ghat]]\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110808112424/http://www.sridasamgranth.com/ Sri Dasam Granth]'',The Sri Dasam Granth Sahib website\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Gurdwaras in Bihar]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurdwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 = \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in India\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = India\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = Guru\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = \n}}\n'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Kangan Ghat,  is situated on the bank of river Ganges, about 200 yards from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]. While [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold bangle there, it is also the place where he blessed mental peace to Pandit Shiv Dutt, by giving him the knowledge of Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji. Guru Sahib Ji taught him what 9 gurus had preached.\n\nThe [[ghat]] is associated whith Guru Gobind Singh's childhood, as he was often found playing with his playmates on the banks of the [[Ganges]].  This [[ghat]] about one furlong from [[Takht Shri Harmandir Saheb]] and is marked by a gateway over which this [[Gurdwara]] is situated in a single room. The river has since receded away to the north.\nhttps://www.allaboutsikhs.com/gurudwaras-in-india/gurdwara-gobind-ghat-patna-bihar\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurdwara Gobind Ghat is also known as [[Gurdwara Kangan Ghat]]\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110808112424/http://www.sridasamgranth.com/ Sri Dasam Granth]'',The Sri Dasam Granth Sahib website\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Gurdwaras in Bihar]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "name_user": "LKametVentures", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding links and correcting errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurdwara_Gobind_Ghat"}
{"title_page": "1966 Cincinnati Bearcats football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1966\n| team = Cincinnati Bearcats\n| conference = Missouri Valley Conference\n| short_conf = MVC\n| division = \n| record = 3\u20137\n| conf_record = 2\u20132\n| head_coach = [[Chuck Studley]]\n| hc_year = 6th\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = Jay Bachman, John Parker\n| stadium = [[Nippert Stadium]]\n| champion = \n}}\n{{1966 Missouri Valley Conference football standings}}\nThe '''1966 Cincinnati Bearcats football team''' represented [[University of Cincinnati]] during the [[1966 NCAA University Division football season]]. The Bearcats, led by head coach [[Chuck Studley]], participated in the [[Missouri Valley Conference]] (MVC) and played their home games at [[Nippert Stadium]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1966\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 24\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1966|team=Dayton Flyers|title=Dayton}}\n| site_stadium = [[Nippert Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, OH]]\n| score = 7\u201323\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 1\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1966|team=Wichita State Shockers|title=Wichita State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Cessna Stadium|Veterans Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita, KS]]\n| score = 20\u20136\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 8\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1966|team=Xavier Musketeers|title=Xavier}}\n| site_stadium = Nippert Stadium\n| site_cityst = Cincinnati, OH\n| gamename = [[Cincinnati\u2013Xavier rivalry#Football|Rivalry]]\n| score = 13\u201325\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 15\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1966 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n| site_stadium = [[Tulane Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[New Orleans|New Orleans, LA]]\n| 